==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} [[melior]] ''better'' +[[-ism]]. Reportedly coined by British author [[w:George Eliot|George Eliot]] in her letters, published in 1877.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The view or [[doctrine]] that the [[world]] is neither entirely [[bad]] nor entirely [[good]], and can be [[improve]]d through human [[effort]].  Understood as an [[intermediate]] outlook, between [[optimism]] and [[pessimism]].
#* '''1966''', "[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,901869,00.html Forever Beginning]," ''Time'', 6 May,
#*: At the convention, the official mood was traditional Methodist '''meliorism'''.

